# Step 1: Inner Surface Reconstruction from Endoscopic Video

## Background

The goal is to build a **surgical navigation "GPS"** pipeline. Step 1 focuses on reconstructing the inner surface of an organ from endoscopic video and producing a unified 3D mesh + camera trajectory that can later be registered to a pre-op CT/MRI model.

### Two complementary tools

| Capability | Endo-4DGS | EndoGSLAM |
|---|---|---|
| **Deformable tissue modeling** | ✅ HexPlane 4D deformation | ❌ Static Gaussians only |
| **Camera pose tracking (SLAM)** | ❌ Requires known poses | ✅ Real-time tracking |
| **Depth estimation** | ✅ Rendered + Depth Anything | ✅ From RGBD |
| **Dense 3D reconstruction** | ✅ Per-frame point clouds (`--pc`) | ✅ Incremental map |
| **Real-time** | ❌ Offline training | ✅ >100 fps rendering |
| **Dataset** | EndoNeRF (known poses) | C3VD (colonoscopy) |

**Key insight**: Endo-4DGS handles deformation but needs pre-computed camera poses. EndoGSLAM provides real-time camera tracking but assumes static scenes. For your GPS system, you need **both** — camera localization AND deformation-aware reconstruction.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This plan has **two possible approaches**. Please choose which direction you want:

### Option A: Quick — Extract 3D mesh from your existing Endo-4DGS training (recommended to start)
- Use the **already trained** pulling/cutting models
- Run rendering with `--pc` to export per-frame point clouds
- Fuse them into a single mesh using Open3D (TSDF fusion or Poisson reconstruction)
- Export camera trajectory from the known poses
- **Result**: A colored 3D mesh + camera path, ready for CT registration in Step 2
- **Effort**: ~1-2 scripts, works today

### Option B: Full pipeline — Integrate EndoGSLAM for real-time SLAM + Endo-4DGS for deformation
- Clone and set up EndoGSLAM in a separate environment
- Run EndoGSLAM on your endoscopy video to get camera poses + initial reconstruction
- Feed those poses into Endo-4DGS for deformation-aware refinement
- **Result**: A complete real-time capable pipeline
- **Effort**: Significant integration work, new dataset format needed

> [!NOTE]
> I recommend starting with **Option A** to get a working 3D reconstruction quickly, then upgrading to Option B for real-time capability later.

## Proposed Changes (Option A)

### Surface Reconstruction Script

#### [NEW] [extract_surface.py](file:///home/mi3dr/Endo-4DGS/extract_surface.py)

A script that:
1. Loads a trained Endo-4DGS model
2. Renders all views with depth maps (already works via `render.py --pc`)
3. Performs **TSDF volume fusion** across all frames using Open3D:
   - Back-projects each depth map to 3D using known camera intrinsics/extrinsics
   - Integrates all frames into a TSDF volume
   - Extracts a watertight triangle mesh via marching cubes
4. Saves the fused mesh as [.ply](file:///home/mi3dr/Endo-4DGS/data/endonerf/pulling_soft_tissues/points3d.ply) and camera trajectory as `.json`
5. Optionally launches an Open3D visualizer showing the mesh + camera path

### Camera Trajectory Export

#### [NEW] [export_cameras.py](file:///home/mi3dr/Endo-4DGS/export_cameras.py)

A script that:
1. Loads the EndoNeRF dataset poses ([poses_bounds.npy](file:///home/mi3dr/Endo-4DGS/data/endonerf/pulling_soft_tissues/poses_bounds.npy))
2. Exports camera positions and orientations per frame as a JSON trajectory
3. This trajectory is what gets mapped onto the CT model in Step 2

## Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
```bash
# 1. Generate per-frame point clouds (already verified working)
python render.py --model_path output/endonerf/pulling --skip_video --pc --configs arguments/endonerf.py

# 2. Run surface extraction (new script)
python extract_surface.py --model_path output/endonerf/pulling --iteration 3000

# 3. Verify output files exist
ls output/endonerf/pulling/surface_reconstruction/
# Expected: fused_mesh.ply, camera_trajectory.json
```

### Manual Verification
- Open `fused_mesh.ply` in MeshLab or Open3D visualizer to visually confirm it looks like the inner tissue surface
- The mesh should show the tissue without surgical tools (since tools were masked during training)
- Camera trajectory points should form a plausible path along the surface
